The beginnings of Taiwan date back to the 15th century, when the 15th century sailors coined for the island the name of Ilha Formosa, or beautiful island.
In 1624, the Dutch East India Company established a base in southeast Taiwan, where it began the transformation of indigenous grain production practices and used Chinese workers for rice and sugar plantations.
In 1683, Qing Dynasty forces (1644-1644–1912) took control of the coastal areas of western and northern Taiwan, and declared Taiwan a province of the Qing Empire in 1885.
In 1895, after the defeat in the First Sino-Japanese War (1894-1895), the Qing government signed the Treaty of Shimonoseki, which ceded the sovereignty of Taiwan to Japan, which ruled the island until 1945.
